            <Title>Step 2: One paragraph</Title>
            <Synopsis>Expand from your one-sentence story idea into one short paragraph that describes very roughly how events are going to unfold.

This can be in a 3-act-structure if you want.

You can also follow the example from Randy Ingermanson and try to find “three disasters” plus an ending”.</Synopsis>
            <Notes> Take another hour and expand your one-sentence summary to a full paragraph describing the story setup, major disasters, and ending of the novel. This is the analog of the second stage of the snowflake. I like to structure a story as “three disasters plus an ending.” Each of the disasters takes a quarter of the book to develop and the ending takes the final quarter. I don’t know if this is the ideal structure, it’s just my personal taste. 
If you believe in the Three-Act Structure, then the first disaster corresponds to the end of Act 1. The second disaster is the mid-point of Act 2. The third disaster is the end of Act 2, and forces Act 3 which wraps things up. It is OK to have the first disaster be caused by external circumstances, but I think that the second and third disasters should be caused by the protagonist’s attempts to “fix things”. Things just get worse and worse. 
You can ultimately use this paragraph in your proposal. I recommend that you write a paragraph with five sentences: 
The first sentence tells the backdrop and story setup. 
The second sentence explains the beginning up to the first disaster. 
The third sentence describes the first half of the middle, up to the second disaster. 
The fourth sentence describes the second half of the middle, up to the third disaster. 
The fifth sentence explains the ending. 
If you’d like to see some examples of one-paragraph summaries, look at the example Snowflakes included in Snowflake Pro. You can reach these from the File menu which has a submenu named Open Examples. You’ll find a complete explanation of the theory of the Three-Act Structure in chapter 8 of my book Writing Fiction for Dummies. </Notes>
        </Document>
