        <Document ID="29D4E0E2-5011-41AE-9C4D-1ACE971A49D0">
            <Title>Step 4: Grow the Story</Title>
            <Synopsis>Turn each sentence of your summary paragraph into a full paragraph.

Every chapter (except the last) should end in a disaster.

The end of the final chapter is the end of the book (obviously).

</Synopsis>
            <Notes>If you’ve done the first three steps, you should have a good idea of the large-scale structure of your novel. So now just keep growing the story. 
Take several hours and expand each sentence of your summary paragraph into a full paragraph. All but the last paragraph should end in a disaster. The final paragraph should tell how the book ends. Write this in present tense, like this: “Jack sells his cow in town for some magic beans. When he comes home, his mother throws the beans out the window . . .” 
This is a lot of fun, and at the end of the exercise, you have a pretty decent one-page skeleton of your novel, which we’ll call a short synopsis. It’s okay if you can’t get it all onto one single-spaced page. What matters is that you are growing the ideas that will go into your story. You are expanding the conflict. 
Later, you can expand this into a synopsis suitable for a proposal, or you may find that this is all the synopsis you need. You can decide that question later. 
If you’d like to see some examples of short synopses, look at the example Snowflakes included in Snowflake Pro. You can reach these from the File menu which has a submenu named Open Examples. I have a thorough discussion on writing synopses in chapter 9 of my book Writing Fiction for Dummies.</Notes>
        </Document>
