            <Title>Define the Authors </Title>
            <Synopsis>Create one page per author </Synopsis>
            <Text>Define the Authors 



Name:

Address:

Phone:

E-mail:

Bio:


</Text>
            <Notes>When you write a proposal for your book, you’ll need to tell the publisher a bit about yourself. The usual kind of information you need to give them is: 
Your full legal name (this will go on your contract) 
Your mailing address (so they’ll know where to send your contract) 
Your phone number 
Your e-mail address 
Your “author bio” — a biography of a few paragraphs that tells some interesting facts about you and why you’re the best person in the world to write your novel. Some points to ponder:
If you are especially similar to your target reader, that’s crucial to mention. 
Your educational background may be important, if it says something about your ability to write your book. 
If you have very specialized knowledge, mention it here. For example:
If you’re writing a time-travel novel and you’re a physicist, say so. 
If you’re writing a romance novel set in Norway and you speak Norwegian, say so. 
If you’re writing a legal thriller and work in the legal profession, say so. 
Any life experience you have that is relevant to your novel is important to mention here. (Your publisher may use it to try to get newspaper/radio/TV interviews for you.) 
This is not the place to talk about how much your mother loves your book or about how you’ve been an avid reader since you were five years old. (Publishers assume both of these are true.) 
Keep your bio short — no more than a few paragraphs — and put your best foot forward, but don’t lie. Lies will catch up with you sooner or later, and it can be ugly if they don’t catch up on you until you’re exceedingly famous. </Notes>
